# Module Mounting Rules

## The Contract
All modules mounted by this shell MUST implement `EngineModule` from `@base/engine-core`.
- Never mount a module that doesn't implement `mount()` / `unmount()`
- Always `await module.unmount()` before removing a module from the DOM

## Shell-Side Mounting Pattern
```vue
<!-- src/components/modules/ModuleMount.vue -->
<script setup lang="ts">
import type { EngineModule, ShellContext } from '@base/engine-core'

const props = defineProps<{ module: EngineModule; context: ShellContext }>()
const container = ref<HTMLElement>()

onMounted(async () => {
  if (container.value) await props.module.mount(container.value, props.context)
})

onUnmounted(async () => {
  await props.module.unmount()
})
</script>

<template>
  <div ref="container" class="module-container" />
</template>
```

## ShellContext Construction
Build the ShellContext once at the app level and inject it:
```typescript
// src/composables/useShellContext.ts
import { EventBus } from '@base/engine-core'
import { useRouter } from 'vue-router'

export function useShellContext(): ShellContext {
  const router = useRouter()
  return {
    eventBus: new EventBus(),
    locale: 'en',
    navigate: (path) => router.push(path),
  }
}
```

## Rules
- One `ModuleMount` component per module slot — do not nest raw DOM manipulation
- Pass context via `ShellContext`, never pass the Vue router or Pinia store directly into a module
- Modules communicate with the shell via `eventBus`, not via Vue props or emits
- If a module needs UI rendered in the shell (modals, toasts), it emits events — the shell listens and renders
